    <name>
				<text>8.2.3.5 Exercise 2x2 linear system no solutions v2 (NOT IN QUIZ)</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Consider the following linear system of equations: <span class="math display"><span>\[\begin{matrix}
    \displaystyle{{@eqq1@}} \\
    \displaystyle{{@eqq2@}} \\
\end{matrix}\]</span></span>

</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

    <li>
        <p> Consider the matrix form <span class="math inline">\(AX = B\)</span> of the system and identify <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span></p>
    </li>

    <div>\(A=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</div>
    <div><br></div>

    <li>
        <p>Find the determinant of <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span>: </p>
        <p><span class="math inline">\(|A| =\)</span> [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>Determine if the system has no solution, a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions.</p>
    </li>
    <p>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>

    <li>
        <p>If it has a unique solution or infinitely many solutions, these are:</p>
    </li>

    <p>\(x =\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] </p>

    <p>\(y =\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] </p>

    <p> Give all the solutions if there is more than one. If there are no solutions, fill the gaps for \(x \) and \(y \) with the word <b>null</b>. </p>

</ol>
[[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
  <li>
<p> In matrix form \(AX = B\), the matrix \(A \) is \[ A = {@AA@}.\]</p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> \( \det A = {@determinant(AA)@} \). </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> Since the determinant of \(A \) is \( 0 \), we already know that the system has either no solution or infinitely many solutions. Note that if we multiply the first equation by \({@kk@} \) we obtain \[ {@kk@} \cdot ({@lhs(eqq1)@}) = {@kk@} \cdot ({@rhs(eqq1)@})
    \Leftrightarrow {@expand(kk * lhs(eqq1))@} = {@expand(kk * rhs(eqq1))@} \] which is in conflict with the second equation. Therefore, the system is incompatible, i.e., there are no solutions.</p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
<p> We have already found that there are no solutions to this system. As indicated in the question, you should enter the word <b>null</b> in both \(x \) and \(y \) as an answer to this part.</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
